Polar Visualization Tool for Aggregated Radial Densities
This Python tool generates a segmented polar heatmap to visually compare multiple datasets of aggregated radial density, typically obtained from molecular dynamics simulations or local structure analysis (like Radial Distribution Function $g(r)$ or a related quantity). Each input file is represented as an angular segment of the polar plot, allowing for direct comparison of density distribution across different systems or atomic pairs.
Key Features
"	Segmented Visualization: Represents multiple input CSV files on a single polar plot, dedicating an angular sector to each dataset.
"	Polar Heatmap: Uses pcolormesh on polar axes to display density (Z-axis, color) as a function of radial distance (R-axis) and segment ($\theta$-axis, angular).
"	Data Aggregation: Processes scattered data (distance vs. density) and aggregates it into configurable radial bins ($\Delta R$).
"	Flexible Configuration: Allows defining custom limits for the radial axis ($R$) and the color scale (density $Z$) for fair comparison, as well as setting segment labels.
"	Advanced Aesthetics: Includes halo effects (black/white border) on labels and radial ticks to enhance visibility over the colored background.
"	High-Quality Output: Generates a 300 DPI PNG file (polar_density_comparison_N_files.png).
